reviewText: This is not a great movie but,compared to the last one,this is masterpiece theatre. Harmless fun

To read more of my reviews you can visit: thescreencave.com
_________________________________________________

In a role not too different from years past, Dwayne Johnson stars in Brett Ratners Hercules. The movie follows Hercules as the son of Zeus, who after enduring 12 labors (tests), is haled as a god all over Athens. When Hercules and his half-brother Iolaus (Reese Ritchie) venture with their comrades to aide Lord Cotys in strengthening their army in return for gold, deception is sprung upon them. With a ruthless leader and a strengthened army, Hercules and his remaining fleet must fend for themselves and avenge the deaths of Hercules wife and kids.

Without question the movie is adventurous with great battle sequences and seeing the weaponry at hand. The charisma of Dwayne Johnson is awesome as you can tell he is comfortable in his role after doing similar roles in The Mummy Returns and The Scorpion King; among others. There is an element of fun as the film doesnt try to take itself too seriously. The pacing worked well considering the movie ran 97 minutes and kept moving without hitting any lulls along the way.

From the very first trailer you got the sense that there was hope for the film as it looked like a more serious take on the Hercules character. And with that, the signing of Dwayne Johnson brought more attention as he had the look for the part. Then as more trailers began sweeping the cinemas and the internet the more cheap looking it started to look like. The trailers were bombarded with special effects and almost came close to the Pompeii trailer a couple months back. After watching the film, as a whole, sadly their wasn't much to it as the plot was thin and didn't have much going for it.

There aren't any other stand-outs in the film other then Dwayne Johnson as he was the center piece of the entire movie. However, that in case is the problem since we don't really get a sense of desperation or feeling for any of the other characters. Receiving a PG-13 rating, the movie is directed more as a kids film with the set pieces and dialogue between characters. The pacing of the film was fine but without any character development to really connect with any or most of the characters they all became fillers. By the end of Hercules you feel like you won't remember the film after a week or so since it lacked any depth or from the simplification of the script.

Although the movie does have its flaws, the entertainment factor will help to overlook those issues in the end. What you get is a pure popcorn movie with a standout actor in Dwayne Johnson and all his glory.

Nine Things about the Film "Hercules" [USA, 2014]

1. This is a very interesting version of the Hercules legend. But you need to know, the legend has been reinvented. The trailer for the movie is kind of misleading. This is not the Hercules you are used to..

2. The birth of Hercules, his childhood, and his legendary 12 labors are all pretty much done before the opening credits.

3. In this movie, Hercules is really just a human mercenary, with a team of warriors helping him out. His nephew has the sole job of making up the legends of Hercules and spreading them around to give Hercules a badass reputation.

4. It is set in a time when people are starting to doubt the existence of gods and magic, but still need something to believe in.

5. This movie has some really impressive, epic battle scenes.

6. Hercules's companions are a diverse and entertaining group. Ian McShane is especially good as Amphiaraus, who does drugs and gets "visions from the gods". Some of these visions come true, and some don't.

7. The movie does a good job of illustrating that some monsters you have to battle are psychological ones.

8. There are a few moments that contradict the movie's attempt to stay grounded in reality. That's annoying. But there aren't very many of them.

9. If you want a movie full of gods and monsters, you will leave the theater angry. If you like to see military battles, and a reflection on how heroes are made, you may appreciate it. This movie is certainly smarter and more layered than most movies of this type.

Director, Producer and Script Writer Skills do matter and the results were fantastic.  Solid story line, great sets, outstanding special effects, actors delivered fine performances and Brett Ratner (director) and David Varod (Producer in Charge) teamed together to produce great entertainment.  Brett Ratner directed movies like Rush Hour and David Varod produced movies like the expendables.  Brett and David are my kind of dynamic duo and I hope they team up together in the future.  Many of the poor movies coming out of Hollywood are not the result of the actors;  given good directors, producers and script writers they can mold the actors to deliver highly entertaining films.  I'd like to see a director's/extended cut of this film on Blu Ray.  I will be buying the blu ray.

I was surprised that over 9,500 people reviewed a film with "The Rock" playing Hercules. I did not expect it to be good, but I was wrong. It is a good film, which has lots of action and lots of humor. We are told at the beginning that we will hear the true story of Hercules, and it is true that this version is truer that the myths. It tells us that all of the myths are lies or extreme exaggerations.
Hercules was not the son of the god Zeus. He did not do all the acts attributed to him alone; he had helpers and the labors were not as difficult as the myths claim. He did not kill his wife and children. This was part of his imagined post-traumatic syndrome; someone else killed his family. Furthermore, Hercules did not do what he did to help people, he was a mercenary who insisted on him and his friends being paid for what they did. In the most exciting part of the film, he needed an army of over a thousand soldiers that he and his companions had to train to do his job.
He had five companions: One was so disturbed by others that he sometimes acted like an animal and had to be chained. One was an amazon who was an excellent shot with her bow and arrow, and could even shoot several arrows at the same time. One was his nephew who made up stories about him, stories that became myths. The fourth was a friend since childhood who appeared to leave him near the films end. The fifth was a man who could foretell the future, sometimes.

Typical summer action movie I suppose. Very, very generic and average. The good things first- The Rock certainly looks the part and does a fine job even though I feel his character is a bit bland in this version. Ian McShane is awesome in everything and John Hurt is also a welcome sight. The action is solid but not incredible. The bad? Pretty much everything else. Most of the characters are generic and forgettable. There's too many of them and we don't get to know much about any of them. The plot isn't terrible but it never takes enough time to breathe and let the situation soak in. The ending is also rushed. The biggest problem I have with the movie is that it's yet another version of a mythological figure that tries to be all grounded and gritty. Hercules doesn't really fight any monsters here, instead it's just another generic war flick. They try with some humor to lighten it up but then things get real intense at the end. Somewhat of a clash with these tones, a better score would've helped also. The end credits feature a pop rock song, not exactly my style. Bottom line is this particular version lacks heart and a solid connection to the characters. Perhaps worth a watch, but don't expect much.

This is an interesting take on the legend of Hercules. The idea mainly being "What if Hercules legend was just that- a legend? What if Hercules was a real guy and really he just grew up on the streets later to become a mercenary?" It's an interesting concept.
Unfortunately there is an over reliance on padding, montages, and meaningless back story in this. I'm not entirely surprised, though, as it was directed by Brett Ratner who is a director that takes on interesting ideas and fails to be very good at making them work well. For a little while he was successful with this because he was taking ideas that felt fresh so they held themselves by novelty. Now, he's mostly relegated to remaking old ideas. This can be fine, but Brett Ratner has very little talent (if any) so there's always going to be a problem. Especially with directing.
This movie is a cool idea, but I think where it really fails is that they decided to tell the story from the middle. When Hercules is already an established legend. I think this was done so they didn't have to own the idea whole heartedly. Maybe it failed as a story, but succeeded in other ways (and somehow they got to do a sequel) they could just take it all back and decide he is more legend than man after all. This is the type of half baked trash I expect from Brett Ratnet at this point, but it's still a real shame. Maybe if they wanted to start here that would be fine if they owned the concept entirely. Don't constantly go back to his past exploits for no reason. We get it. There is no magical creatures in your telling of Hercules. In reality the myths are more powerful than reality (as reality dictates this is always the case anyway). Don't constantly elude to the fact that magic really doesn't exist in this world, but then constantly go back and forth ("Maybe he is the son of Zues. Who could say?").
Anyway, it's a great idea given to a terrible director so it doesn't live up to the potential of the concept.
I liked the casting choices here. Dwayne Johnson has become a skilled and likable action lead, and he fits Hercules fine (even though he's clearly Hawaiian, but don't worry I won't tell anybody ;) ). I liked all the actors cast as Hercules friends as well.
The story is inconsistent and full of padding. Whoever wrote it didn't really seem to know where to go with the story as they constantly show either montages, or long scenes of talking where nothing of importance is shared other than to express maybe Hercules is the son of a god, maybe he's not, but he certainly is famous. Oh, but really that wasn't a hydra. It was dudes with masks on.
Luckily the movie is fairly short, so you don't have to worry too much.
Also Ian Mcshane is in this so for me it's automatically fun at least for the 5 minutes he gets to be on screen. I especially liked his characters sensibility.
All in all I'd say this movie is fine as a rental. It's ok to see it once, but I wouldn't buy it. It's a great idea made by people with low IQs so it's maybe half of a good movie and half of a meandering drivel movie. Disney's Hercules is more consistently interesting, but this movie does have it's moments. Unfortunately they decided to make it "realistic" so none of the interesting stuff about Hercules shows up except when he throws a horse with a man riding it.
The movie was Me at best, I didn't like the humanising of Hercules.

Scenery was outstanding, plot not so much and characters were played fantastic by the actors given the dialogue they were given. I had high hopes with this release of a Hercules film. Unfortunately, the 'writing' is just more lame Hollywood 'reimagining' of what the story is. I mean, the story is already written. Just get The Rock huge and beastly, have him perform the "labors" for Hera, and call it a wrap. Who doesn't want to see an actor that actually resembles what one might think of as Hercules take on crazy beast after insane monster?!? I for one did, and if your looking for that best look elsewhere.

To sum up the movie, without any spoilers: Incredibly typical action/war movie. Opens to show the obvious plot. The characters proceed along the expected plot line and, alas, the expected unexpected twist followed by the foreseeable setback. Then the slightly necessary rally cry (have to keep the movie somewhat interesting). And finally, the incredibly foreseeable conclusion. This is the extremely predictable and typical action/war movie. There is little done to veer from that plot line and it is obvious throughout the move. However, there is a reason that that plot line is so popular. (Make whatever you want of that.)
I found this movie hardly enjoyable, the acting was mediocre though the characters were well developed enough to have obvious motivation, which was also blatantly stated several times in the film. This was not the typical Hercules story, in fact it almost pick up where others leave off but wastes the name of Hercules. They could substitute any character in place of him and the story would lose nothing. He is just the name and face of a successful mercenary.
On a more positive note, this film is gracious to women, while they are still dressed provocatively and have unreasonable body standards, there is no woman in place as purely a love interest. Incredibly there is a woman among the most influential characters who is only sexualized by her appearance.  There are two somewhat dramatic fight scenes that are choreographed well on a budget. The visual effects are well done. You will be able to follow and predict the story line with little effort. That being said, there is a small chance that it will put you to sleep first.
I conclusion, I do not recommend this film and would suggest a classical war movie in its place. Even a spy movie would be better.

If you are looking for an action/adventure film that puts a new spin on classic Greek mythology, then look no further. This movie will keep you engaged as well as entertained the entire time. The movie does a great job putting a realistic spin on the well known and often told Greek myth of Hercules. In the very beginning of the movie, it starts off as you would expect. They tell the narrative of Hercules' birth and his twelve labors. Then, without warning you begin to see that Hercules is nothing more than a mere mortal who has a band of warriors who help him decimate all that stands in front of them. The nephew of Hercules helps promote his myth along with his greatness in an effort to help them make their fortune as they work for one kingdom after the next. A nice twist is when the movie begins to revert back to the myth of Hercules and his greatness as a half mortal/half God.
It's a great movie. Interesting take on the Hercules tale.

Fantastic take on the old tale of a guy just trying to do right by the people he was foisted upon to live with.  While it showed some of the myths to be a bit overblown in his case, it doesn't discount that all of the legends aren't as they are put out to be, and leaves room for some truly fantastic acts.  After all, an ordinary someone doesn't pull what Hercules did at the end and just walks it off.
One thing that really endears this to me is its symmetry to 2004's The Alamo, and Billy Bob Thornton's Davy Crockett.  In that movie Davy never claimed to do all the amazing things that tales said of him, but in the end still left a mark of legend about himself. It was really at that point that Santa Anna had lost the war. He just didn't realize it later until San Jacinto.

Dwayne Johnson delivers a solid performance as a man who is also a myth, created by legend.  In this telling of the demi-god's tale, Hercules is the leader of a band of skilled mercenaries.  This mercenary team includes a story-teller who shamelessly markets the groups exploits as proof of Hercules' connection with the gods.  Though filled with well crafted action sequences, the heart of this film is a thoughtful exploration of how the Hercules legend developed and grew.  Is he the son of Zeus, or simply a very powerful and wise warrior?

This film could have become something truly special.  Unfortunately, as with many action films, great promise is offered in the first act, many fantastic and exciting problems are created in the second act, but then the third act solutions to these fantastic problems end up being a real stretch of credulity.  It's just difficult to believe Hercules and his handful of mercenaries can be trapped and then go head to head with thousands of soldiers.

Even with that fault, this film is a real hidden gem.  It had the misfortune to be released at the same time as Guardians of the Galaxy, so Hercules was completely overshadowed in its theatrical release.  Still, this is a good film, well worth your time.

The action in this movie was pretty decent, and Dwayne Johnson played the role of Hercules quite well. In fact, I'd say if it weren't for him, the movie would probably have been a flop. That's because there wasn't anything really special about it; it feels like just another action ancient war film. There is an interesting plot twist at the end, but other than that, I didn't find anything overly special about the story. Another thing to keep in mind while watching this is that the writers seem to take a more practical reasoning to explain happenings in the film, and the spirituality in the film is reduced. This film is certainly no Clash of the Titans. Over all, I'd definitely recommend. There is not too much overtly sexual content, but a handful of innuendos are stated throughout the film. Violence is about what you'd expect for a PG-13 film. Thus, teenagers and mature children should be able to watch this.

I'll start by saying that I totally expected this movie to be much more about the mythological figure than it was.  That's not to insinuate that this is a bad thing, mind you.

This movie is based on the comic book published by Radical Studios.  I was unfamiliar with the source material prior to watching the movie; that did not matter.  I found myself engaged with the tale told here from the beginning.  There were two things that held my attention most while watching this movie: the fact that Hercules seemed much more mortal than I expected (even in regard to his strength) and the fact that THIS Hercules didn't seem to be the hero that I have always associated with that name.

I won't spoil the story, but I WILL say this: the revelations told near the end of the movie shed quite a bit of light on why Hercules is the man that he is throughout.  I understood the nature of his personality and the journey that began in the back story before the movie begins.  Hercules seems to have found a bit more of his way by the end; I almost literally cheered for him by the movie's end.

The villains of the story were what you'd call "classic' villains with a bit of a historic leaning to them.  How Herc and company get pulled into the conflict was handled quite well.

If you're looking for something that's more akin to "Clash of the Titans" style fare, you might find yourself disappointed.  However, if you're looking for an action film with some humor, this might be one that you can get into.

Dwayne Johnson is Hercules. Here stands a man of great strength, but with a broken soul. Perhaps not the legend that we know, but still a man who has done impossible things and not because he has Godly blood coursing through his veins or does he. Accused of a dastardly crime, chased from his Homeland, he is relegated to being a mercenary that sells to the highest bidder to "help" while relying on the words of his cousin Iolaus, played by Reece Ritchie, who stirs people, kingdoms and soldiers with his embellishment of Hercules' Labors. Ian McShane nearly steals this movie as the affably comical Amphiaraus, a seer who's visions from the Gods lead this band of merci-men plus one woman Atalanta, an Amazon, played by Ingrid Bols Berdal. John Hurt is well John Hurt and plays the character of Lord Cotys with great finesse. Rufus Sewell barely recognizable as Autolycus a childhood friend of Hercules has always stood with him even in the face of stupidity. Aksel Hennie  as
Tydeus and Joseph Fiennes as Eurystheus are terrificaliy tragic figures. This is a great cast, great writing and Ratner does a great job! The fighting sequences are tight and the story line like this legend is the story of a true Hero, of true Heroes.

Just prior to watching this, I viewed the other one, the Legend of Hercules.  Both are fine entertainment movies, but this version with Dwayne Johnson incorporates a lot of liberties to up the ante over the traditional story.  So if you're fine with the loose interpretation and view this as a hero flick, you'll likely enjoy this.  But if you're a traditionalist and don't want somebody messing with your myths, this version may be a bit irritating.

When I heard that Dwayne Johnson was doing a Hercules movie, I was really looking forward to it -- "The Rock" can be a decent actor in the right role, and with modern special effects, the mythical story could be done right.  I've had a love of Greek Mythology since I was a little kid.  Sadly, Johnson, the writer, director and producer decided to make a more "realistic" version, claiming that various Hercules "stories" were distortions of much more mundane adventures.  In effect, Hercules and his companions are con men who distort his accomplishments to build his reputation for profit.

This movie has pretty good action scenes, but most of the joy I expected from the movie was removed by making it realistic instead of mythical.  I would have rather seen something more like the original Greek Myths.

Greek mythology and comic books were about the only things I would read when I was a kid, and as an adult I still love them.  So when I saw this movie, I was pretty excited.  It's a modern take on the classic, finding the truth in the Hercules story but still being fantastical.  The action scenes are well worth watching for some mindless fun, and for those wanting an engaging story and characters, I think there is enough there for you too.  There is also a nice balance of humor to the serious, and the cast is quite eccentric in a good way.  It's a great movie to sit down and watch on the big screen or to have on in the background on a small screen while doing something else.

This is quite a good version of the old Hercules tale, this version has Hercules as a mortal man (although still with far fetched strength and the ability to keep going after being mauled and stuff).  Hercules is basically a mercenary for hire who will join anyone in battle, for gold.  He has a pose  of warriors who go everywhere with him including Atalanta, a hot well toned Amazonian warrior (Ingrid Bols Berdal) who not only goes into deadly battles in pretty much a medieval bikini top and short skirt but has even more over the top fighting skills than Hercules, and can dispatch countless enemies with her archery skills.  He also has a cousin who voices Hercules battle action as a loud commentary behind a wall of soldiers and compares what he's doing to myths of battles against lions, serpents and other Greek mythological creatures that he wants the enemy to believe actually happened.

Hercules is a fun sort of tongue in cheek Greek medieval era battle movie that's overall plot is fairly predictable.  It's the type of movie where the main heroes miraculously avoid getting killed by arrows raining from the sky, who can fight multiple people at once and only look like could come to harm when their attacker will be killed from behind and another of the hero group will give them a smile that says, see I got your back.  Dwayne Johnson does a good job as Hercules, and if you get a DVD with extras you can see the wig and makeup transforming him from the bald headed "The Rock" into the Greek mythical legend.  Dwayne also talks about how he always wanted to play Hercules and how he got injured in a wrestling stunt show but was determined to recover and make the movie as he knew it got shelved for a year, it probably wouldn't ever be made.  I found the extras to be as interesting as the movie was entertaining.

Witty dialog saved this movie.  The interesting thing is that half the movie attempts to debunk the idea of Gods, then gives super powers to an entire squad supporting Hercules. The action is so over the top to ALMOST be comical, but you have no thrill watching the cartoonish action. The Road Runner has more realistic action than this movie. The acting is not exceptional but isn't going to destroy your faith in humanity either. The special effects are top notch. This could have been an awesome movie if it was not so hypocritical. The dialog could have been inspiring if the movie was not done with comic book type action.  Seriously, a guy throwing knives and taking out waves of enemy, a woman shooting multiple arrows hitting multiple targets and killing all instantly. Finally the last feat of Hercules goes against everything the movie tried to build, which completely destroyed the whole suspense of disbelief.  Even the sword fights among mere mortals were poorly choreographed and cartoonish. Luckily I was not disappointed as I had low expectations to start with. The humor in the movie makes it worth watching however.

It took a while before getting into this version of Hercules.  The green screen effects cheapen the picture, initially annoying us.  But as the story developed, we began to appreciate that this was meant to be a more humanistic portrayal of the Hercules legend, leaving out direct actions by the gods.  It climaxed most gratifyingly at the end, where the film gave an alternative to the legend of how, why and by whom Hercules and his family were made to suffer.  All in all, the movie held our interest and we were satisfied.

Really, this is a 4.5-star movie. For what it is. Which is, a fun movie. What made it a cut above other fun movies, and earned it the extra stars:

- It's not stupid. The movie doesn't assume the audience just wants cheap thrills. Yes, this is a good action movie, but it had something to say about perception, reputation, myth (and our desire to indulge in it) and even, if you think about it, PTSD. That it had anything to say at all was a huge, and welcome, surprise.

- It didn't follow the formula regarding its band of heroes. I won't say anything more about that.

- The female warrior was pretty cool.

- There weren't any unnecessary romances, again bucking the formulaic a bit.

- The formulaic parts worked really well. As someone else said, it has a nice touch of humor, and Hercules' right-hand man (Rufus Sewell) was really fun. I'd be interested in seeing him in other movies.

If you're already interested in seeing this movie, but worried it might be a bit dumb, you'll be pleasantly surprised. Enjoy!

Disclaimer: I am Dwayne Johnson fan...  What that said, I will grudgingly admit the film did not live up to expectation.  Compared to Game of Thrones (for example), I was anticipating more authenticity regarding some of the character development and aesthetics (i.e. ancient Roman or Greek accents, hygiene (body hair & teeth), and even temperament/mannerisms in some cases.  I was also hoping Johnson would do an unrecognizable transformation into the "legendary" Hercules, but to be fair, this movie was not about the legendary character.  Hercules was re-casted to being just a man with hero-like characteristics - essentially "The Roc"... Despite all of that, I (still) enjoyed the movie.  The cinematography, costumes, and acting was all pretty good.  As touched on before, it portrayed Hercules from a completely different prospective (mortal vs. immortal) and in a different context than mostly all other films and books. I personally found appreciation in the different spin on the mythological character - and occasional comic relief experienced throughout the film as well.

Simply Awesome. intelligent take on the Legend of Hercules. Try to remember that the story of Hercules was a very very old oral tradition long before it was written. Long before there was writing. For instance, (and not to be a spoiler), part of the mythos the legend of Centaurs...is probably a very old memory (no telling how old), of a time when the art of horse riding was not widely known. People hunted horses for food - not taming and riding. Such would be the memory of any tribe or people who first encounter-----the shocking sight of a man on a horse. It had not been seen or even envisioned by any people for a very long time.before such a meeting.

Similarly, when the Spanish came to conquer the Americas, horse riders were viewed by Native Peoples as a two headed 6 legged monster..or even gods. Here too the Spanish capitalized on that shock, while Native Peoples gradually killed off the Conquestadors And their horses. When that happened the Original Peoples adopted the art of horse riding ---and they too have their "Horse Legends". The plains tribes became legendary Horse Warriors and Hunters. The blood lines of the original Spanish horses introduced in the Americas, and bread by the Original People l runs strong to this day in the west and southwest - to this day. And that is a "True" legend.

Remember that the tale of Hercules was written down in a time when writing was still novel, "literate" people were still very rare, even kings and queens likely could not read or write a word. Aaah scribes. What has come down to us are just scraps and pieces that has somehow survived time. That similarly the oral traditions - the racial memory - were already dimmed by immense time.when they were set to stone and vellum. We are no better than the scribes and historians of that ancient day - we can only catch a glimpse - and mourn what was lost for the telling of even more ancient days.and Not recorded.

In Ancient Greece (cradle of Democracy) many were the families that claimed direct lineage to Hercules. It was these people who commissioned the writing of the Oral story of Hercules. Even that version of the story that has come down to us,(and others like ir) still informs and in part directs our notion of Freedom and Democracy even as it did in days of old.

This is a thoughtful, intelligent, action packed story of Hercules. However it is told, the message is the same, Battle evil, find courage and strength in persistence, strive for better lives for you and your people, battle evil for in the end you choose your fate and like Hercules -become a Hero.

We are a civilized people, our best weapon of choice IS the written word, negotiation, petitions, even your vote.....The pen is mightier than the sword. These days the battles for good are no less fierce than the Labors of Hercules, but the lesson is still the same -for persistence in the face of insurmountable odds, persistence and courage fighting the good fight- Will Prevail. Be a Hero. Vote in this Democracy that was born in the days of Hercules.

I like Dwayne Johnson's movies, like I like John Wayne or Tom Cruise movies, as there are certain expectations you want when you see a main star headlining a movie.  Hercules was actually well made.  It made you think about the legend of Hercules and how it may have been based upon the reality of what Hercules actually did.  There is a nephew portrayed to tell the legend as he would exaggerate to help Hercules win over the masses he was fighting for.  This was a neat perspective for a movie.  It is full of action, feeling, love, tragedy, pathos.  A lot of Dwayne Johnson's movie seem to have this and this is what makes watching his movies enjoyable.  Definitely recommend!

I really love Greek mythology, heck I even have the Ten Plays by Euripides sitting on my computer desk. The whole time I watched this movie I really thought the title should of been "A Man Called Hercules." That is essentially what this movie is about, you get no epic Greek tale just a bastardized version of if Hercules was an average man how would he accomplish these so called "feats" and how his legend was embellished to advance him into "godhood."
For what its worth it's a pretty enjoyable movie once you get away from that wanting to see a Greek myth feeling. Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson is such a likable guy in pretty much any movie he's in, and damn those arm veins can just about pop out of your screen; no 3D needed.

I liked this more than I probably should have. A general description is a merger between Conan the Barbarian and the Hercules TV series from years back.

There have been many iterations of the Hercules story.  This time he's a jaded mercenary, fighting for cold hard cash with a band of equally profit-minded cohorts.  Hercules' calling card is his renown as the son of Zeus.  But here, even he isn't necessarily 100% sure of his divinity.  It's an effective twist to the Hercules mythos although one that has been used dozens of times in other stories.

Yes, the action scenes are fantastic and the treachery is laid on thick, as you'd expect.

Mostly I enjoyed this because Dwayne Johnson brings an undeniable charisma to the role, and because the predictable plot and characters are executed well.

In short, the movie sets itself on a well-traveled path, and arrives safely at its destination.

An interesting take on this story from classic mythology, this movie was unexpectedly good.  I anticipated a formulaic action flick with updated special effects repeating and renewing fun and campy old movies.  While there were definitely elements of that, this version of Hercules took a surprisingly fresh approach to the myth and I quite enjoyed the movie as a whole.  The only complaint I have, and it's very minor, is that there was a lot of exposition left out in the plot.  It felt like I missed parts, not unlike going to refill popcorn and coming back to wonder what happened and how we got from point A to point Q.  Overall, I was pleasantly surprised by how much I enjoyed this movie.

Sadly this movie failed to meet it's potential. I must admit I'm a Dwayne Johnson fan and I could sense the earnest effort he put into this role,but alas for the umpteenth time, the "Olympian-size" gravitas the subject requires was once again unrealized. I was pleasantly surprised at director Brett Ratner's job "behind the camera" especially in light of his lack of experience directing this genre of film. .Unfortunately this movie  is plagued by a mediocre script,rife with modern-day colloquialisms and expletives,and rather uninspiring pre-battle" inspirational" speeches and exhortations. This film's high points, for me at least, occurred within the first ten minutes of it's start and during the last twenty minutes or so of it's conclusion. I did find the very "non-supernatural" explanations regarding several mythological creatures very plausible,especially that of centaurs and Hades' Cerberus. I did constantly have to "check" my incredulity while viewing,and reminded myself that the film is based on a graphic novel and generally eschews mythical accuracy. I do extend kudos to Ian McShane,Rufus Sewell and Joseph Fiennes whose presence served to elevate the movie's acting,even though the dialogue was often "wince-producing".If,by chance,a sequel or even a prequel is being pondered,the first ten and last twenty minutes of Hercules should serve as the production's "blueprint".

The Rock is great - looks better than ever. I guess I'm a bit of a purist though. They took a few too many liberties with the story of Hercules. I'm afraid there are many people - who don't read the classics, or don't read at all -- that will be taking this for the real story. It is a BIT more believable from a modern-human standpoint, but we can't change the old stories just because we feel like they need to be changed to match the times. That's not why they survived all these many years. But that is Hollywood, I suppose. They've done the same with Noah, and Lincoln, and whomever catches their fancy on a particular day. I just wish they would be a bit more up front with a statement about "this is fiction/fantasy BASED on the story of x." I have actually talked to people who take a lot of these movies for true. But back to Hercules - it's pretty good.. enjoyable. Pretty people abound. Lots of fights for those who like that.

Interesting from the standpoint of the action and a semi-interesting story plot.  Is this Hercules really a demi-god (son of Zeus) or just a really buff muscle man surrounded by myth??  The story tantalizes with the possibilities but is never conclusive.  Either way, he is impossibly strong and whips up on the bad guys in some really whoopee scenes.  His side kicks (comrades) contribute largely to his success in battle and they are no slouchs either.  Lots of action, but the storyline like Hercules' strength sometimes borders on the absurd.  Still, it's entertaining for the guys who like action.  Probably a little gory for the under 12 crowd.

Dwayne Johnson is a far superior actor even if he has had a few duds himself.  I expected a good cheesy action flick and got a much more realistic (by comparison) epic.  That is another thing that made it good in my book: the fact that there was very little in the way of mysticism and the supernatural.  I could easily say I enjoyed this at least as much as Troy, more than Alexander, and much more than the new Conan movie.  If anything negative is to be said for it, I'd say it left me wishing someone would make a worthy Conan movie (long overdue).

For some reason, the creators of this movie thought that the myths surrounding the Labors of Hercules were too fantastic for modern audiences to accept so they had them become false PR for Hercules' band of mercenaries.  (The brief scenes depicting the myths are actually the best in the movie.)  In their place, they created what one supposes they thought were more realistic adventures for Hercules.  Unfortunately,  the story of the new Labors is quite predictable; and the supposedly realistic martial skills of Hercules and his companions are beyond believable, at times even ridiculous-- but they are in keeping with modern films' idea of action.  The filmmakers also get an F for their knowledge of Greek history.  Nonetheless, Dwayne Johnson is such a likable presence that, despite the negatives, the movie is enjoyable and well worth a view for those who love action films set in the ancient world.  This film is no worse that the old Steve Reeves movies and certainly more pleasant to look at.

Surprisingly intriguing story of deceit and payback, city leaders seeing Hercules as obviously strong but do not believe he is really the son of Zeus.  In this 2014 film, Hercules has a well-trained team having saved each life that stands by him from a former battle.  However, as the story continues, it is up to Hercules to give backing to the legend of his birth, leaving everyone wondering at the end "it is real or is it Memorex" a statement well understood by many who watched TV 35 years ago.

The special effects are well done while Dwayne Johnson gives his usual excellent performance.  What I love about these films with Johnson is that you can enjoy them with your kids without the progressive's firing F bombs every five minutes to try to pretend they control the media. Predictable but still enjoyable for that genre.  I thought Dwayne Johnson did a credible job and I've always enjoyed him the numerous action roles he's been in. The part where one of his trusted sidekicks takes the money a leaves has been done a number of times but an argument can be made for the justification for it. I was relieved when Hercules thru several cathartic adventures was finally able to finally lay to rest the emotional baggage he'd been carrying around since that tragic incident with his family. Did I jump up at the end of the movie and fist pump the air yelling "Hooray for Hercules"? Not Really!  Did my eyes well up when his personal futurist gave him THE pep talk that allows him to finally become the man he always aspired to be and needed to be or all would be lost. Nope!  But did I enjoy the movie absolutely. Hell, I used to like the Steve Reeves movies when he played Hercules or someone akin to him and they were poorly dubbed.

There's something about a "remake" of older movies that makes me hesitate; some have been quite disappointing, with more emphasis on crazy stunts, or special effects, sometimes overshadowing the story line---or worse, lousy acting.  Well this film did NOT disappoint me.  In fact, it was different from a lot of movies that feature a "super hero" (main) character, such as that played by "The Rock," Dwayne Johnson.  He didn't portray an out-of-control, invincible warrior, but more often exercised restraint, recognizing that war leaves deep scars on both sides.  This film moved along quickly, and I found the cinematography more colorful than the drab, almost tawny tones seen in other recent films featuring urban scenes, and scenes with non-stop action (excluding filming in diminished light which naturally reduces visible colors).

Frankly, this movie entertained me on several levels, and I intend to watch it again.  It was well-cast, had little if any gratuitous violence, good CGI (but not overwhelming), and a great surround soundtrack.  Also, for a "combat" action film, Hercules (2014) had far less offensive language (thus its PG-13 rating) than the majority of action movies I've seen the last few years.  Dwayne Johnson makes a believable action hero come to life once again!

Many nice special effects with great costumes. If you enjoy Greek Mythology with a different spin to Hercules, then you may like this.

Hercules, Dwayne Johnson, the son of Zeus, performed twelve labors making him a legend.  But the movie is the time after the twelve labors where hercules and a band of misfit mercs earn gold, doing odd jobs here and there.  Until Ergenia, Rebecca Ferguson, a princess and daughter to the King of Thrace, John Hurt, offers much gold for Hercules to train the King's army.  Rhesus, Tobias Santelmann, is a supernatural warlord who will stop at nothing to destroy the King.  Can Hercules train the King's army to defeat an unholy onslaught of a supernatural warlord and his army?

I didn't like the direction the story took. I understand it was based off a graphic novel, I guess I wouldn't have liked that either.
SPOILERS!
I'm a big mythology buff, so I didn't like the idea of Hercules being a regular guy who had help from friends and just a reputation of being a demigod. There was that time he said he didn't know his father, where I thought he really was and just didn't know it...but no.
The story had some flaws as well. These might be considered nitpicking, but they play an important part in my review. When Hercules is talking with Autolycus about their take--after battling the pirates--he mentions that they're almost to their goal. But just before that, he let half of them go. He mentions many times in the movie that they are mercenaries and they're in it for the money, so it makes no sense to default on half your potential profits.
I didn't like how crazy strong they made him either. He was knocking guys through walls, pushing over giant statues, pulling giant shackles from stone, and getting bit by huge wolves. Stuff that lots of completely normal men can do, right? The movie was quick to show that Cerberus, hydras, and centaurs weren't real and this really is just a normal world we live in, but then give him strength like that.
So to sum it up, I kept expecting the revelation of him being a demigod after all, but was let down when that never happened.

Certainly a different take on the Hercules tale, yet entertaining to watch. Actor's performance is decent, visual effects are OK, story is OK, have to mention that story is a lot different from what anyone would expect from a Hercules movie. I found most interesting the plot twist on the movie.

Would I watch again? Probably not, but it was fun to watch.

If they had done this right, there could well have been 12 movies; one for each of the fabled labors.

this much better than I expected it to be, but frankly if they could stretch out the Harry Potter series into a zillion sequels; the classics were already sitting there waiting to be brought to life without any (or minimal) artistic license and fabrication.

Fortunately this production is blessed with a star cast and a fairly decent script.
The production values are excellent.

I am getting tired of the archery thing; the whole Legolas (LOTR) elven archer par excellence, the exquisite Chinese martial arts film "Hero" with the "sky blackened by the Qin armies" routine. It's not offensive, but it's too obvious and it would have been more interesting to see the Amazon warrior engaging in more swordplay to underscore the legendary prowess of the Amazons.

The opening scenes are breathtakingly brilliant; thus my conclusion that a multitude of sequels could have been realized had the producers not gone for the fast and easy money.

The scary/crazy bug-eyed dude with a very bad case of neoclassic pan Hellenic PTSD is a very amusing and interesting character.
I suppose in those days; pre-Prozac Nation and all that, if you had PTSD, you just went around killing people; which seemed to be a very socially acceptable activity in those times; they certainly seemed to be a really blood thirsty lot back then.

Anyway, I gave it 4 stars just for the benefit of the doubt and it is more than just palatable entertainment, especially given such stellar performances by actors like John Hurt, who can deliver a solidly engaging performance in whatever role he's offered.

The plot is superficially but adequately intelligent; which is a God send, rather than subjecting the audience to a moronic simple minded good vs. evil topped with eye candy beefcake script.

Overall it was disappointing but not horrible and ultimately forgettable.

Me: "Believable? But there was literally no resemblance to any kind of actual historical realities at all. The Scorpion King was more accurate to real life events. And then there was the Legolas chick... and the bone... whip... and the CGI... and the... with the... and..."

For the reviews complaining that the Labors of Hercules were over sooner than they would have liked, had they Actually read ANY synopsis previous (say on a site like IMDb) they would have known that a lot of the story takes place AFTER the Labors were performed. Hey, it was publicized but as always, it seems, people see something and think it will be what they expect rather than taking time to do a little extra research. Anyway I thought everyone in the film played their roles well for the storyline given. The film in tone reminded me of the TV series Hercules The Legendary Journeys so if you ever watched that show the film is similar in tone and humor. I also liked how there was an up-in-the-air quality to one story point; watch the film and it becomes obvious. Any nitpicks I have are minor given certain elements in the Hercules myth that is primarily known. Beyond that I definitely liked this take better than the film that preceded this one's release in 2014.

During the end credits, it was revealed that the characters were based on a comic book.  Had they shown those graphic novel type animations at the beginning of the movie, I think I would have liked Hercules much more than I did.  What I thought were deep flaws in the movie, may have been completely intentional.  For instance, Hercules would wack an enemy with his caveman club and the guy would fly twenty yard through the air.  A scene like that didn't seem to fit in with the overall feel that the director seemed to be going for.. unless you know it's based on a comic..

It was very disconcerting how the movie kept shifting from seriousness to camp.  I also didn't like Dwayne Johnson in this.  I thought he did a pretty awful job in his dramatic scenes, and simply giving him a beard didn't do enough to mask the wild eyed fake-serious wrestling persona underneath.  In the most serious of scenes, I always half expected him to turn to the camera and yell out, 'can you smell what The Rock is cooking!' What does that even mean?!?  But knowing now that it's based on a graphic novel, I would have given the movie more poetic license and I wouldn't really care how dramatically Dwayne Johnson can act.  And did you notice how white everyone's teeth was?  Everyone's teeth were so bright that I thought it was carelessness on the director's part, but again, perhaps even that was part of the artistry of the comic series.  My honest reaction to the movie was 3 stars, but had I seen it with the right mindset I may have given it 4.

Was once again scared to rent because of the mixed reviews.  Glad I ignored them and watched the movie anyway.

I think people expected something going into the movie and therefore rated it down because it wasn't what they expected.

I honestly don't understand why people cared SO MUCH that Hercules wasn't doing the Labors.  Would it have been cool to watch him slaying monsters the entire time?  Maybe.  Does that mean the plot of the movie was bad because he wasn't?  Hell no.

Sure the story was predictable at times but it was a good one.  The casting was well done for Hercules as well as the supporting actors and the pacing of the movie was perfect.  There were never long periods of waiting for something exciting to happen.  Some movies like to throw in a ton of action at the start and some like to throw it all in at the end.  Hercules kept it going the whole time.

Well worth seeing at least one time.  Unless for some reason you might die in 2 hours and can only pick one movie.  Then you might make an exception.  Outside of that, give it a go, and don't let the haters or people who have unreasonable expectations turn you off like they almost did me.

This isn't an incredible movie, but it is a fun movie to watch with some great action scenes. The movie follows Hercules, the "Greek Hero." The thing I particularly like about this movie is that, although Hercules is portrayed as a hero to commoners, the movie watcher has insight to the true nature of Hercules. He is a mercenary who has gained acclaim as a hero by spreading rumors about himself in an attempt to scare foes into surrender before he even has to fight. The 12 trials are born out of embellished tasks for a mercenary (i.e. the hydra is really a group of bandits who wear snake masks to hide their identity). Don't expect Oscar performance, but it is a fun movie with some great and exciting fight scenes and Dwayne Johnson does a great job in his role.

First, Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson definitely looks and acts the part.  On the strength of this movie,he would also have portrayed a much better "Conan the Barbarian" than Jason Momoa.  I'm not familiar with the original comic book this version of Hercules is based on, but I find this movie an interesting departure from the way the titular character is usually portrayed.  Even though a lot of the creatures Hercules faced may have been "fictionalized"(considering the context of mythology and "tall tales"), he's still very much a ultra-competent superhero.  I think Hercules humanity comes across better than most other movies or books that have portrayed him, and "The Rock" does an admirable job of bringing this across.  Whereas he was somewhat stiff & stilted in "The Scorpion King", Johnson has since improved and it definitely shows in this movie.

Truthfully. both of the "300" movies (based on the Frank Miller graphic novel) are more stylish and a bit more graphically violent.  Also, I still prefer the first two Conan movies with Arnold Schwarzenegger as well as the Steve Reeves version of Hercules.  Having said this, Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson does the "sword & sandal" genre proud and definitely stands head & shoulders above most other movies of this ilk, including the non-entity starring Kevin Lutz.  It was actually the second time I watched this movie, and I don't give movies a second chance if they don't impress me the first time.  This movie proves that one doesn't need a truckload of blood and gore to make a good action/fantasy movie.  I enjoy this movie as a "one and done" standalone tale; I wouldn't mind seeing "The Rock" reprise this role in a well-plotted sequel or, failing that, take up the helm of Conan.

There has been a seemingly infinite number of Hercules movies in the past, uniformly worthless as far as I can recall, and I didn't expect any more of this movie than to watch it for a few minutes and then watch something else.  However, I found myself watching it through to the end, and think it is not only the best Hercules movie ever made, but perhaps (off the top of my head, without researching it a lot) the best mythologically-based movie ever made in English.

What follows has some semi-spoilers, so if you actually intend to watch the movie, you might want to stop here.

What makes it the best is not the acting, which is okay but doesn't live up the the generally very-high caliber of some of the actors involved, nor the special effects, which are certainly good enough, but that the movie is not mythological at all.  No gods and goddesses or mythological creatures appear.  Yes, there's a story that Hercules is the son of Zeus, but he doesn't seem to believe it personally.  Yes, he has done the "twelve labors", but as he keeps saying, they are greatly exaggerated.  Yes, he is immensely, amazingly strong, but not of godlike proportions.  He and his companions seem to think that he is merely a very strong human being, although at times they are so taken aback that they clearly wonder; mostly, they seem to think that they are just mercenaries about whom tall-tales have been spread.  This seems to me to a novel enough idea to carry the movie.

You rehash the same tired plot devices employed in just about every single "epic" action film of the last 15 years, and derive the protagonist from characters in culturally resonant source material (purely for name recognition to ensure ticket sales, of course) and you have this latest regurgitation of Hercules' legend. This could be another movie Dwayne Johnson has done throughout his career, with any other title.

You can easily dismiss each member of his dispiriting band of men (and woman) as hackneyed token archetypes. Johnson is the reluctant antihero with the heart of gold, whose moral ambiguity and human imperfections veer toward the path of holy righteousness in about 30 seconds. We can't leave out the wisecracking senior with the "take it or leave it" attitude towards death, because you know, he's been there, done that. The token female warrior with the character depth of a paper plate and the annoying sidekick who allegedly proves he is not the weakest link by offing ONE guy in the last 15 minutes of the movie round out the team. You add a few more expendable characters, two flat villainous villains with the typical motives that reek of villainous villainy, rinse, repeat and you have HERCULES! HERCULES! HERCULES!

While I found this to be a moderately entertaining movie and useful for killing some time, by no means did I think it was a good or great movie.  As many other reviewers have mentioned, the premise appears to be the man behind the legend.  Unlike many other reviewers, however, I cannot agree that this is supposed to be a more "realistic" version of the legend of Hercules.  First, by the protagonist's own admission, his father is an unknown.  Second, the feats of superhuman strength Hercules performs on multiple occasions over the course of the film defy both human limitations and the laws of physics.  Whether or not Hercules is the son of Zeus is left to the viewer's interpretation of these fantastical acts.  The "big twist" is pathetically obvious, and the ending felt rushed.  On a positive note, I can say with certainty that this is the best performance I have ever seen from Dwayne Johnson.  The other characters, while shallow and underdeveloped, are generally likable.  I won't say this movie isn't worth seeing, its just not worth going out of your way to see.

The Rock (nee Dwayne Johnson) has that certain je ne sais quoi, that enigmatic spark that translates onto the big screen and yet somehow director Brett Ratner (the "Rush Hour" franchise; "X-Men: The Last Stand") must have filmed him at wrong angles or on the wrong day of the week because that star-making sizzle that he has just doesn't burn through this screen.  Johnson plays the titular Hercules, a legend in the making.  The film follows a particular exploit in his legendary journeys that seems sure to doom him and his band of merry men (if that remark reminds you of Robin Hood then good, you've been warned that Herc has a band of merry men who help create and aggrandize his legend).  In the end does he really discover that he is a demigod after all?  Watch and see.

Or don't.  If you like action/ adventure flicks with large pitched battles you might come out of this going "okay, not great but not that bad".  If you want more fantasy and more of the Rock's charisma you're going to be a bit disappointed.  This movie is more like a bright and pretty and even cheery "13th Warrior" or "King Arthur" or "Magnificent Seven" than it is a "Clash of the Titans" or "Percy Jackson".  So...choose your myth.

Actually I am a fan of "classic" hero movies, starting with Steeve Reeves' portrayal of Hercules way back when. Usually, I have been disappointed with subsequent attempts at depicting such a powerful, mythical figure. However, I think that "The Rock" performed well in this one and that the story line infused some clever twists in the re-telling of this time-honored myth.  It's a fun movie.

After a certain age, certain movies just don't have the same appeal. You know, when you're 21 and seeing a movie on opening night is just what you do, or ordering tickets in advance " just in case" (in case of what, i don't know, but we rationalized). One you hit 30 you only do it for special movies, but i gotta say, mid 30's and up, you're like " omg, cant wait to see it" and when you do, its always on video (so aging myself saying video) because getting to a movie theater has too many variables to actually execute. Well i watched this in the comfort of my own home, playing hooky from work, laying around with some wine and cheese ( yep, wine and cheese!) I have to say, didn't expect much, i mean, The Rock?? Great to look at, a somewhat entertaining actor, but i thought, this role may be too big for him. Well, very well done, Mr Ratner, Mr Johnson! This was just such a fun movie. It didn't play out too seriously and diverted a bit from the legend that we knew to make it more plausible ( as much as could be) with the right amount of humor, action, story telling, cinematography and graphics  that just made this a great movie. I'm using the word great loosely here, because you have to somewhat realize what you're getting into before watching it. I did see the other Hercules with Kellen Lutz and while that was not on the Pompeii oh-my-god-so-bad level, it was not great...like really not great, mostly because of Kellen Lutz. Just bad casting. But this cast was fun, they had chemistry, and again, this was just a man realizing his potential and eventually living up to it. Go into this with low expectations and you will be greatly pleased.

Okay, as a old guy who grew up watching Steve Reeve's version of Hercules from the 1960s, I was never moved much by later renditions of the hero; even the Marvel comic's Hercules was modeled on that version. But.....Dwayne Johnson does a great job in this role, and is entirely believable as the hero. While the slant of the movie is different from other versions, including the Kevin Sorbo tv series, I was very surprised by the film. By the movie's end, it's fairly apparent that you are watching the Hercules. This Hercules is, at least, a good basis for the legend that books and legends are based on, and as such, is more believable than a lot of other versions. Would I watch a sequel? Yes. Especially if it has as much action as the first one. It's an entertaining film, and its well done, with just enough humor and drama to make it work. I think the big problem for the film was the timing of its release, as a different Herc film came out just before this one, and did awful box office. So this film, had a hard slog toward success, but should do well on dvd and cable.

This is a much better film than most of the movie critics rated it to be. It takes the myth of Hercules and grounds it in reality. Dwayne Johnson once again proves that he has flashes of depth in his acting that a lot of action movie stars do not, and he leads a very nice ensemble cast of characters. While Johnson and Ian McShane get to go a bit further with their characters than the rest, all are very good. And the main point of a movie like this is the action, which there is plenty of. But what a lot of the critics overlooked was the message the movie makes about heroes, how heroes are created, how they are perceived, and the potential in anyone to be one. This is an action sword and sandal that goes a little bit deeper. It is a fuller story than the old Steve Reeves movies. And, in a way, reminded me of the original "Magnificent Seven".
On the technical side, the costumes and sets are beautiful, and the battle scenes are very well staged. The script has a few twists,but nothing that is overly surprising. But I found it a very enjoyable film, and so am writing one of the very few reviews I have written on Amazon.
Would love to see this cast reunite for a sequel.

Incredible action, fabulous acting, and an interesting take on the character of Hercules are tainted by bad writing, which produces this year's biggest mediocrity worth watching.  Corny dialogue and infuriatingly stupid Braveheart speeches.  Armies that follow whoever is leading them like poor A.I. in a video game.  Unexplained and unlikely visions of centaurs.  Stuff like that interjects itself as soon as you you get comfortable with the film.  But these annoyances cannot ruin the host of fun action scenes, funny interactions between the heroes, and reasonable plot twists.

Basically, Hercules' team is an ancient version of the Avengers.  Each member has an incredible skill set, a unique personality, and an interesting (if vague) backstory.  They roam around righting wrongs for coin, exterminating and exposing "monsters" and various bad guys.  All the while propagating the legend of Hercules, the son of a god.  Using this legend to bring in more coin and make their battles easier is ingenious and often funny.

Hercules (the movie) reveals THREE phenomenal actors who need a lot more screen time: Ingrid Bols Berdal, Aksel Hennie, and Reece Ritchie!  These three SHINE alongside greats like Ian McShane and Joseph Fiennes.  Ingrid is the most believable, beautiful Amazon warrior I have seen in film.  Tough, articulate, expressive, and an action star.  Hennie says more with his facial expressions than the Rock said the entire movie.  And he can bring it in a fight like a mad viking on crack.  Really nice.  Ritchie is charismatic and believable, complimenting his costars perfectly.  I was really impressed by these three.  You never expect a movie like this to contain such high quality performances!

Speaking of acting, the Rock is at his best in this movie.  Still kind of stiff and unbelievable, he has trouble showing emotion on film, but he did very well.

So, while I cannot say you should buy this, I CAN DEFINITELY say you gotta see this.  If you love action, fantasy, or mythology, this film delivers.  Again, if you liked the Avengers, you'll like Hercules.

As a fan of the Rock and of this legend in particular I was all about this flick. This film was released around the same time as the other one called The Legend of Hercules so I had to check them both out. Now as I am sure others have pointed out this is not the Hercules you all know. This film is not really about the myths although they are touched upon. This is a more realistic take on the man with new things added but it is an entertaining movie.

Here Hercules leads a band of mercenaries who are hired by a man who wants to see his enemies crushed. So Hercules and his crew go out onto their mission and many a battle ensues. But things are not all of what they seem. Friends become enemies and vice versa as the myth become legend. I have to say that I liked the way the mythical things were used and explained as the film went along. It was a cool new take on Hercules that while not perfect was an entertaining watch.

The acting was really good here particularly that of Hercules and gang as the actors all had great chemistry with one another. Of course Dwayne Johnson was perfect for his role but I don't think this film would have been half as good without the supporting cast they got for his click in the flick.

Director Brett Ratner who is probably best known for the Rush Hour films I think did a good job with this flick that was based on a graphic novel. The action is excellent here with some really cool battles and fight scenes. Like I said this is a more realistic Hercules film so expect the battles to be so, although of course there are still some over the top moments.

This was a good movie and while I did like it I still think I like it just about as much as the other one. it may be because this film was marketed as following the myth and legend so I went in expecting something else. Still its a good movie and the Blu-Ray comes with some great special features. You get behind the scenes stuff, deleted scenes and a great commentary. Also did I mention the ladies in this film are great, especially the merc.

I wasn't extremely excited about the refresh to the original story, but the movie as a whole was good. Solid acting, impressive cinematics, and when you think about it, the direction they went with revamping Heracles's origin fits nicely with the recurring theme of deception and politics associated with the historical era as a whole.

The movie isn't all bad. You get to see Hercules fight all the mythological critters he is supposed to have beaten. You see the birth and origin as told in the legends.
The problem is that the movie goes out of it's way to give a logical explanation as to why the mythical parts of the story became legend; for instance, what was thought to be a multi headed hydra was actually men in disguise. There's nothing wrong with that, I guess. Maybe there are some people in the real who believe Hercules actually existed, who need a logical explanation for the fantastical parts of his legend. Fair enough, I suppose.
Unfortunately the whole point is lost because Hercules still does things that, unless your name was Samson and the power of God was upon you, were not only  beyond the abilities of an ordinary human but definitely reached demi-god status. Not to mention the fact that the statue of the goddess who supposedly never existed, plays a pivotal part in the outcome. Clearly this was meant for irony but along with the seer's ability to see the future, you still get the vibe that maybe the gods of mythology actually were instrumental in shaping the legends of Hercules' life.
Personally I was turned off by the attempt to remove the mythological aspects of the story, but if you are going to go that way, at least be consistent.

Happily, the disarming script doesn't take its theme, mythical background and central character too seriously, and--ironically--that casual "hey, he's just a guy" attitude helps us take this movie much more seriously than we otherwise would; funny how that works!  It's "epic" without the pretense.

Johnson looks the part (no kidding) and based on stories about his preparation for the picture, hats off to him...he knew what it took and he went out and did it.  He's a passably good actor--and not at all like the wooden Steve Reeves of yesteryear (I can hear anyone under 30--the target market here--asking, "Who?")  At least two very legitimate "name" performers--John Hurt and Joseph Fiennes--get an opportunity to overact and do so with gusto, especially Fiennes as the treacherous King of Athens. More good fun.

The film's most obvious weakness is its failure to incorporate Rheseus in the story much past his defeat and imprisonment. "Hey, what's happened to him?" I wondered. I had to look hard to find him.

The picture looks great; the effects and visuals are quite stunning. Even better, it moves well. Two scenes are standouts; the major battle between King Cotyes' army and the forces of the usurper, Rheseus. Whoever was responsible for the scenes of massed military manoeuvers did a great job. I haven't seen this calibrer of hand-to-hand since Braveheart.  The second notable scene--happily--is the very satisfying climax; shades of the old Cecil B. Demille Sampson and Delilah--much more believable, of course. There's some real artistry going on behind the tech tools here, and that's the big difference.  So, yeah--surprisingly--three stars!

It's how the plot unfolds and what happens in the movie that make it a great movie or a flop.  It's for this reason that the twists and turns that the movie took to reach the final climax was refreshing.  The characters were developed just enough to make them plausible.  The reason for the many quests that Hercules embarqs upon (money and fame) ring true to someone who may have really existed.  It had some "same old stuff" twists like his friend coming back to deliver the daring blow to save the boy-king and start the melee, but these were forgiveable when taken all in as a whole.  It was a very great movie with much entertainment bang for the buck.

Dwayne Johnson plays Hercules in an action-packed film directed by Brett Ratner of Rush Hour fame. Well, I wrote Hercules because  (possible spoiler)  it is not exactly that Johnson plays Hercules, one of the most famous characters in the mythology; he plays a mercenary who claims that he is Hercules, leading a group of seasoned soldiers.

So is he really the Greek demigod? Watch the film and you decide. The point is, based on the comic series by Steve Moore, the new film is an attempt to present a more humanized Hercules in an entertaining way.

And the story is something like this. After the rescue mission of his nephew, Hercules and his band are hired by Lord Cotys (John Hurt), who wants him to train the ordinary citizens for the possible war. Of course, the task turns out more difficult than Hercules expected. Well, the story is a typical one. Not bad, not great.

Now, if you want Hercules from the myths, maybe you shouldnt watch this one. If you want an enjoyable popcorn movie with big-budget action set-pieces and charismatic Dwayne Johnson impressive as the titular hero, this is for you.

The Hercules tale is well trodden and yet the there was something fresh and intriguing with Brett Ratners version. Perhaps because the cast was well above the B movie level and the script and story lines were enhanced rather than detracted by the special effects. The result was an unexpected and very pleasant surprise. Dwayne Johnson shows he can match his star power with the likes of well seasoned actors such as Ian McShane, Rufus Sewell, and John Hurt. The humor was an added spice and the pacing was dead on, for the most part. Top notch stunt work, well coached secondary actors and extras and believable settings fleshed out the story in and unexpected and compelling way. Humanizing Hercules and yet honoring the myth puts this version of the famous tale well above the host of other comic book cardboard versions of Hercules that came before.
Ian McShane was particularly delicious in his running commentary and sardonic humor. Good flick.

It would be convenient to pin the disappointments on the director (Brett Ratner), but the direction was not the issue and was actually remarkable considering the unexciting story. Any episode of Xena: Warrior Princess is more interesting than this movie; it performed more like a high budget TV series but with obviously no hope of revealing anything else in the world created. The production was near Gladiator proportions and quality but the story was barely a dribble of the same recipe. There is absolutely no romance evident or implied, no goosebumps moments, and 80s era combat routines. The most thrilling moments were all shown in the trailer and are minimized by the "Hercules was actually just a dude" theme that beats you over the head throughout. Embarrassment for the cast participating was the only strong emotion felt aside from boredom. Though a better story could have utilized the cast effectively, the entire lot of them would be well suited for a Sons of Anarchy spin off series. While it would have been completely bonkers and unfounded, the addition of motorcycles would have improved the experience of the film at least 1 and a half stars.

I've always been fond of the story of Hercules, the son of Zeus and a human woman.  In search of the  quintessential version, I decided to check out this newest movie, directed by Brett Ratner ("X-Men: The Last Stand").  The main draw is Dwayne Johnson, who seems perfect for the role, especially in his bulked up state in this film.  He doesn't disappoint although the film is a paint-by-numbers affair.

I knew what I was going to get going in and that's what I got, although I thought the final scenes were actually pretty well done.  The film opens with sort of a backstory about how Herc had to perform 12 dangerous missions insisted upon by Zeus's wife Hera as payback for hubby's affair.  Most of these are shown in part in the numerous trailers that preceded the film's release in the summer of '14.

Over the years Herc grew into a family man and warrior, serving King Eurystheus (Joseph Fiennes having a good time).  One night Hercules awakens to find his wife and children slain.  He has no memory of what happened but is presumed to have committed the killings and is banished from the kingdom.  As the years pass, Hercules assembles a nefarious cast of associates played by Ian McShane, Rufus Sewell, Aksel Hennie, Reece Ritchie and Ingrid Boso Berdal.  The later plays Atalanta, a short in stature and skirt Amazon archer.  This band of mercenaries are asked by Lord Cotys (John Hurt) to help him defeat an army of baddies led by Rhesus (Tobias Santelmann).  But all is not what it appears to be.

The film runs its course with bits of humor, bits of Ms. Boso Berhal, and bits of dislodged PG-13 body parts.  In short, the film is what you would expect with perhaps a hint of credibility due to the casting.  Still, don't look for any Oscars.

If there are awards due, it should go to the look and feel of the Blu ray transfer.  It's a doozy.  The video is 1080p resolution with a 2.40:1 aspect ratio.  In a word it looks spectacular.  Robust colors, excellent detail shows off the fine work of the film's craftsmen (armor, shields, makeup, and clothing).  There are no abnormalities or defects in the picture.  Likewise the killer DTS-HD Master Audio 7.1 (hello!) soundtrack really stands out.  The sound effects which range from stampeding horses and chariots to swamp creatures are mixed to perfection.  The perfect musical score resonates throughout the speakers.  The dialog is clear and perfectly placed.  This is demo quality stuff.  Subtitles are available in English SDH, French and Spanish.  Here are the extras:

*Audio Commentary
*The Bessi Battle (HD, 12 min)
*The Effects of Hercules (HD, 12 min) -- Interviews.
*Hercules and His Mercenaries (HD, 11 min)
*Introduction (HD, 6 min)
*Weapons! (HD, 5 min)
*Deleted & Extended Scenes (HD)
